Ut in reciperatoriis iudiciis. ‘Reciperatores‚’ generally three in number, were appointed by the praetor to decide on some issue of fact which required no knowledge of law; Sigonius de Iud. 1. at. Hence there was no reason against these being picked out on the spot from persons present in court, instead of being taken from a fixed list as the ‘iudices’ were. So we find Cicero, Verr. a. 3, 59 and 60, complaining oi Verres for not naming ‘reciperatores de conventu! The point of comparison between the senate on this occasion and 'reciperatores' lies in the words repente apprehensi.

Candoris, kindness oi heart. Ovid credits Salanus with ‘candor' for his sympathy with him in his exile, although their acquaintance was but slight. Ov. Pont. a. 5, 5.
